\ls2\ilvl0\cf0 II.	The Career of Napoleon Bonaparte\
\pard\pardeftab720\fi720\ri0\sl360\slmult1\sa200\qj\partightenfactor0
\cf0 The defeats suffered by France in the war of the second coalition and the inability of the Directory to handle domestic problems satisfactorily do much to explain why the time was ripe for an overthrow of the government. Most Frenchmen wanted a government which would preserve the revolutionary heritage and provide a final victory in Europe and had become embittered about the revolution and wanted it ended. Bonaparte\'92s accession to power did bring an end to a decade of revolution. They recognized that for a successful coup d\'92\'e9tat they needed a military man.\
The drafter of the constitution proposed to have three consuls, one for foreign affairs, second for domestic affairs and a ceremonial figurehead who was to be Bonaparte. Bonaparte had other plans: he pushed through a constitution giving almost all power t a first Consul, chosen for ten years, and that would be himself. \
Napoleon was a son of a poor Corsican noble. He was able to study at French military schools and at Paris. He became lieutenant at the age of sixteen and eventually became a statesman.  \
The first time Napoleon Bonaparte had entered the spotlight of French revolutionary history was when he was given the charge of the artillery. His plan was not unique but he did have the ability and foresight to put it into effect. He was given the command of Army of Italy in the war of the First Coalition though it was considered minor; he made it the most important of the campaign. The final victory of France over the coalition resulted in large measure from his brilliant strategy and tactics. Without authorization he brought the war and coalition to an end by signing with Austria the Treaty of Campoformio in 1797. Then lead an expedition against Egypt on 1798, as a first step towards British India. The most important long-range result of the expedition was achieved by the scientists and other learned men founded the science of Egyptology, which was based in large part on the Rosetta stone, discovered on this expedition and later revealing the secrets of Egyptian writing. He had a monopoly on the news reaching France from Egypt so he was able to able to create a false impression in France that he was consistently victorious in Egypt. \
\pard\pardeftab720\ri0\sl360\slmult1\sa200\qj\partightenfactor0
\cf0 The consulate was the period of Napoleon\'92s most constructive achievement. He laid down the institutions-administrative, financial, legal, and religious-which were to form the framework of 19\super th\nosupersub  century France and thus considered as one of the most important periods of all French History.\
In 1802 he maneuvered successfully to be named \'93Consul for Life\'94 and two years later he proclaimed and crowned himself Emperor of French. He extended the control of France over European countries. He was also known as \'93Little Corporal\'94.\
\page \
\pard\pardeftab720\li1080\fi-720\ri0\sl360\slmult1\sa200\qj\partightenfactor0
\ls3\ilvl0\cf0 III.	 The Militarist and Map-changer\
\pard\pardeftab720\fi720\ri0\sl360\slmult1\sa200\qj\partightenfactor0
\cf0 These two also became titles of Napoleon Bonaparte. Militarist because he was at war most of the time he was in power. His art in war is also popular today that a textbook about his strategy and tactics have been made. He became the model for generals in the American civil war. He was also the first to incorporate and apply all the principles devised by the military writers of the 18\super th\nosupersub  century.\
In here the four French theorists that influenced Bonaparte is discussed. First is Marshal Maurice de Saxe who advocated relentless pursuit of a defeated enemy to complete the victory won on the battlefield. Then General Pierre de Bourcet in which he learned about the use of artillery. Baron Joseph Du Teil laid him down the principles for mountain fighting. Last is Jacques de Guibert, the most advanced of these writers on military theory.  Guibert also prophesized Napoleon\'92s coming. He predicted a state akin to republican Rome, which would almost inevitably lead to the rise of a great genius who would first assume dictatorial powers and then a throne and completely reform the military and political system. \
Napoleon excelled in getting his men to the decisive place at the right time. He drove home the necessity of advance planning to achieve desired results. To Napoleon the aim of the tactical changes had been to gain greater mobility and maneuverability. \
The chapter showed how Napoleon changed the map because of his conquers. Because of his military skills he conquered most of Europe. It was not only Europe whose map Napoleon affected. Because of his economic strategy against Great Britain, the latter was forced to annex several colonies to create other markets.\
This chapter also includes a chart of Napoleons fights with his major enemies, dated from 1799 were he assumes power until 1815. His major enemies were Austria, England, Naples, Portugal, Prussia, Russia, Spain, Sweden, and Turkey.\
