\ls4\ilvl0\cf0 IV.	The Lawgiver\
\pard\pardeftab720\fi720\ri0\sl360\slmult1\sa200\qj\partightenfactor0
\cf0 This chapter is about how Napoleon Bonaparte manipulated the legislature to create a constitution that will favor him and how he manipulated the law to rule everyone and submit to his will, how he became the dictator leaded to becoming the emperor and what are his powers during his reign. \
This chapter offers a chart of the French Government under the Constitution of the year III or 1799-1800. The chart includes the central government legislative process and local government electoral process.\
Napoleon centralized the government of France. From the consul to the mayor of a village holds together.  These enabled him to get things done and furnished him the desired men, money, and order.\
France desperately needed for its laws uniformity just like the revolution and the consulate had given its administration because at that time France was guided by many laws such as customary and common laws including 366 local codes of law. Napoleon enacts a new legal framework for France, known as the "Napoleonic Code." The civil code gave post-revolutionary France its first coherent set of laws concerning property, colonial affairs, the family, and individual rights. Accordingly this code became the greatest glory of Napoleon. This code impressed many governments that it was adapted by more than 35 states and the 19\super th\nosupersub  century became the great century of legal codification. \
\pard\pardeftab720\ri0\sl360\slmult1\sa200\qj\partightenfactor0
