\ls5\ilvl0\cf0 V.	The Financier and Economist\
\pard\pardeftab720\fi720\ri0\sl360\slmult1\sa200\qj\partightenfactor0
\cf0 One of the first goals of Napoleon was balancing the budget because he realized that his government would not be able to remain in power despite military victories if he did not restore some order to the finances.  He did rely on tribute, but levied numerous new taxes which led to one of his outstanding fiscal achievements, the creation of a solid financial administration. His sugar-coating policy included substituting larger proportion of indirect for direct taxes so that the average Frenchman would not know just how much he was paying.\
Napoleon\'92s contribution to taxation policy lay in asserting the principle that taxes should be fair and stable in practice as well as in theory, and in initiating a general and complete assessment of real property. His conception of the importance of state credit and of the means of improving the government\'92s credit rating was one feature of his financial policy. The bank of France was another feature of Napoleon\'92s fiscal contributions. \
He also conducted reforms on Agriculture and commerce for which the most notable innovation in the field of commerce was the establishments of chambers of commerce in numerous towns and his most long-range contribution to this field was the improvement of transportation.  France had for the first time the Ministry of Manufacturers and Commerce and the first modern state to have a court for industry. The government tried to make use of the machinery more widespread, established technical schools.\
Napoleon favored capitalism by extending to other areas such revolutionary reforms as freedom of work, abolition of serfdom and feudal burdens, the suppression of internal customs and tolls, uniform weights and measures, and the possibility of converting land into movable property. He did much to foster French industry. \
\pard\pardeftab720\ri0\sl360\slmult1\sa200\qj\partightenfactor0
