\ls6\ilvl0\cf0 VI.	Relations with the Church\
\pard\pardeftab720\fi720\ri0\sl360\slmult1\sa200\qj\partightenfactor0
\cf0 Two elements in the religious situation were intolerable to Bonaparte. The existence of several different religious was the first-an impossible situation to a despot desiring a classical type of unity and centralization in the state. The other was the separation of Church and state.\
Napoleon undertook negotiations with the Pope for the purpose of arriving at a concordat or religious agreement. He adapted dual policy towards greater religious tolerance in accordance to the Declaration of the Rights of Man, subjecting the church to the state by suppressing the monasteries and by adopting a Civil Constitution of the Clergy, which made the church branch of the state. But there are conditions underlying these, first the Pope had to promise not to permit British goods to enter his ports in the Papal States, and the clergy had to take an oath of loyalty to the Constitution.  No papal bull or other communication could enter France without the approval of the government.\
The aim of Napoleon for doing this was for financial banking and to remove the church as a source of opposition to his regime. The clergy\'92s salary came from the government to increase government\'92s control over the church.\
From the concordat the Catholic Church also gained financial advantages and end to the schism in the church. The bishops gained the right of naming cures and priests.\
It was political rather than ecclesiastical affairs, however, which caused the greatest difficulty between Napoleon and Pius VII which led to the arrest of the Pope in 1808. Such treatment to the head of the Church heightened the opposition to Napoleon in deeply Catholic countries. It was a major factor in ferocity of the Spanish fighting. It also made a tremendous impression on Belgium and the Rhineland, where ultramontanism was strong.\
\pard\pardeftab720\ri0\sl360\slmult1\sa200\qj\partightenfactor0
