\ls7\ilvl0\cf0 VII.	The Educator\
\pard\pardeftab720\fi720\ri0\sl360\slmult1\sa200\qj\partightenfactor0
\cf0 Education in France today is distinguished from that in other major western democracies by its centralized control. Such centralization springs from the existence of an influential teaching corporation which was the creation of Napoleon Bonaparte.\
Both the National Assembly and the Convention decreed the organization of \'93Public Instructions common to all citizens, that part which is indispensable to all men being free\'94. The convention added on September 15, 1793, that instruction would be divided into three progressive ranks of primary, secondary, and higher education. This was the first time such principle had been introduced. Napoleon based his educational program on that of the Revolution. \
The constitution of the year III laid down the basic principles of such a national system of education: the national government would pay for the lodging of primary school teachers; national institute was given the responsibility for \'93collecting discoveries and perfecting the arts and sciences\'94.  Starting Year XII young men would not be enrolled as voters unless they were literate and could carry on a mechanical occupation.\
Bonaparte discovered that he should have personnel upon whom he could rely to administer his policies. He therefore personally devoted considerable attention to education after his military and diplomatic successes had made him all-powerful within France.\
He expected two things from the schools. First was the training of middle class boys to be civil and military leaders. Secondary education was for him most important and since he was a militarist, he wanted rigid military discipline in the secondary schools. Second he wanted the educational system to be uniform. This aim of him led to a neglect of primary education and neglect of education for girls. He thought the place of a woman was in the home. \
He distrusted free research in higher education. The theoretical and liberal aspects were to be eliminated. Free thinking anywhere was suspected. The government decided what books might be used. \
One of Napoleon\'92s contributions to education was the establishment of the Imperial University, a state teaching monopoly in order to offer a uniform and complete education; it encompassed all levels and types of instruction. Basic teachings of this school were fidelity to the Emperor, the imperial monarchy and the Napoleonic dynasty.  His reason for creating this was to get a body of properly trained and oriented teachers, and have a means of directing political and moral opinion.\
Hampered by a lack of resources, Napoleon was unable to erect the kind of educational structure he wanted. But his work in the field of education cannot be accounted a complete failure from his viewpoint. He achieved his immediate goal of having the schools prepare and train functionaries for the government and the hierarchy from classroom teacher to Minster of Education has given the French educational system stability and continuity. \
\pard\pardeftab720\ri0\sl360\slmult1\sa200\qj\partightenfactor0
\cf0 \
\page \
\pard\pardeftab720\li1080\fi-720\ri0\sl360\slmult1\sa200\qj\partightenfactor0
\ls8\ilvl0\cf0 VIII.	 The Propagandist\
\pard\pardeftab720\fi720\ri0\sl360\slmult1\sa200\qj\partightenfactor0
\cf0 Prior to the French Revolution, public opinion was of relatively minor interest to rulers of continental European countries. The French revolution brought, and Napoleon Bonaparte continued in theory mass participation in government. Interested in propaganda as a means of self-aggrandizement as well as for furthering government policy, Napoleon kept the spotlight constantly on himself. \
The greatest importance of Napoleon\'92s propaganda is that he was the first one to use the machinery of government in a systematic fashion to control public opinion and that he used it positively to formulate favorable as well as to prevent unfavorable opinion. He was the forerunner of dictators none of whom would try to force a program without for which he did not have public support, perhaps gained by a total control of the information available to his subjects. \
Newspaper was one of Napoleon\'92s medium to put across his message. For religious news, he established Journal des Cures to replace all other religious papers, which he had suppressed. This is to present Napoleonic point of view. Fear of the press must have played a role in him for limiting the number of provincial papers, each supervised by the prefect of that department. \
Another negative means of controlling public opinion was censorship. There was censorship of letters, of the press, and of books. Publication was forbidden if the book was held to be contrary to the interest of peace, the state, and public order.\
Napoleon devised two means of communicating with his subjects; orders of the day and bulletin. Both dealt with military subjects, but they differed in their audiences. Bulletins were subjected to civilian population for which the purpose is to win public opinion; most orders of the day spoke to the army, but on occasion they were addressed to residents of newly conquered territories. \
The entire governmental machinery, civilian and military, was used to distribute propaganda materials. Napoleon is important as being the first dictator to devote such large share of his attention to public opinion. He spoke directly and frequently to his subjects. \
\pard\pardeftab720\ri0\sl360\slmult1\sa200\qj\partightenfactor0
\cf0 \
\page \
\pard\pardeftab720\li1080\fi-720\ri0\sl360\slmult1\sa200\qj\partightenfactor0
\ls9\ilvl0\cf0 IX.	Catalyst of Nationalism\
\pard\pardeftab720\fi720\ri0\sl360\slmult1\sa200\qj\partightenfactor0
\cf0 Nationalism has been the dominant force of the 19\super th\nosupersub  and 29\super th\nosupersub  centuries. It is not a natural phenomenon but a cultivated sentiment which is the product of historical factors. It demands loyalty to the nation over other loyalty. Napoleon constantly referred France as \'93great nation\'94 rather than as \'93great country\'94. He looked on this new force primarily as something that would foster his own cause, first by overcoming factionalism within France. In order for France to remain great, it would need a united front of rulers and ruled; thus the role of nationalism became entwined with that of his dynasty.\
Accordingly, Germany furnished the prime example of a nationalism engendered by the Napoleonic period. It forged in a short period of time the most important non-French nationalism on the Continent. Napoleon refused to think there were people who felt themselves to be Germans. The organization of the Confederation of the Rhine unwittingly promoted a feeling of nationalism. The execution of a single, country man in 1806 contributed greatly to the feeling of oneness which transcended the bounds of individual German states. \
The writings of cultural nationalists cleared the path of activity of the political nationalists, for which they followed afterwards the footsteps of cultural ones. \
In short the war or conflict against Napoleon Bonaparte led to the development of the nationalism of the other nations and states. His territorial arrangements promoted the awakening of the nationalism. By reforms outside France Napoleon created political nationalism. The principles of the French Revolution produced elsewhere in Europe the same feelings of a national unity as in France. Changes that did much to facilitate nationalism included the creation of administrative hierarchies and the forming of citizen armies. Thus Napoleon\'92s greatest contribution to nationalism is a negative one. But this fact did not lessen his impact on European political life of the 19\super th\nosupersub  and 20\super th\nosupersub  centuries. \
\pard\pardeftab720\li1080\fi-720\ri0\sl360\slmult1\sa200\qj\partightenfactor0
\ls10\ilvl0\cf0 X.	The Legacy\
\pard\pardeftab720\fi720\ri0\sl360\slmult1\sa200\qj\partightenfactor0
\cf0 \'93The Napoleonic Revolution\'94. By the definition a revolution, is a successful movement, effecting far-reaching changes in a short space of time. Napoleon\'92s legacy of change had three components: first, those items he wanted to bequeath to posterity; second, the unforeseen outgrowths to his policies; and third, the changed conditions brought into being as a reaction against his regime.\
In his march across Europe, Napoleon called himself a \'93soldier of Revolution\'94. The reforms which had been instituted in France he carried it to every place where he obtained control. Napoleon reveals himself as a classicist, the man who believed in one universal standard. \
Napoleon aided the rise of the middle classes outside France. It is no accident that the bourgeoisie was most attached, and the nobility most hostile, to his regime. Introduction of the civil code, with its equal treatment of all individuals, and centralization of government with its implied elimination of feudal rights, contributed to this development. \
In social revolution, the improvement was in the legal status of the peasants, a natural corollary of the breakdown of feudal privileges. In some localities the nobility retained most of its rights, and the social reform remained incomplete. There was an improvement in the treatment of the Jews though not everywhere but they had the right to worshipped. \
Like most dictators, Napoleon frequently relied on public works to distract the people from politics and to leave lasting monuments to his regime. \
\pard\pardeftab720\ri0\sl360\slmult1\sa200\qj\partightenfactor0
\cf0 Another legacy of Napoleon was the definition of the rules of literary property, equivalent to copyright law, by a decree. Napoleon also paid a little attention to public health.\
\pard\pardeftab720\fi720\ri0\sl360\slmult1\sa200\qj\partightenfactor0
\cf0 It is in the government and administration where Napoleon made the greatest impact; his concept of a modern state-centralized, acting directly on individuals without intermediaries, and treating these individuals as citizens rather than as subjects. In his centralization and in his police force introduced the military system into government. Though he did not initiate the use of the plebiscite, he used it frequently enough to set a precedent which was adopted by later rulers. \
Many of his institutions were retained: the University of France, the Concordat rule, the bank of France, his various legal codes, and most of all his methods of warfare. \
There are results to his rule that he undesired: the Europe-wide distrust of the French as a warlike people, and a desire to hold France in constant check; the Congress of Vienna could not find a lasting solution to the problems of Poland and Belgium, of Germany and Italy, because it disregarded the feeling of nationality which he stimulated by his reforms and territorial changes; and Britain was able to extend its colonial empire.\
Napoleon was the motive force in the making of History. Although a creature of circumstance to the extent that a career as his was possible only in a time of turmoil, Napoleon was far from being a mere creature of historical determinism. According to historians \'93the Napoleonic hallmark was enduringly stamped on France, on Europe, and beyond\'94. \
